DocDel,<br><br>
Thanks for your thoughtful analysis of the situation. I disagree with you on the &quot;exclusion&quot; view. <br><br>
The handfull of 'NamVets on this site over the past few months have kept the site alive. A lot of very constructive work has been done here.<br><br>
I am not aware of any instance where anyone was &quot;excluded&quot; because they expressed another point of view in a dignified, respectful, civil, manner, in the interest of debate, learning, and productive communication.<br><br>
I feel that others chose not to post because they found some of the historic thermonuclear displays of passion disturbing in language and content. I agree that these unfortunate episodes did not serve the site well at all.<br><br>
On the other hand, I feel it is reasonable to expect indiviuduals who find themselves demeaned, insulted, and otherwise subjected to abuse for no reason other than that they exist, to react in kind.<br><br>
For exapmle, on the Forum I interacted with a CO who was a very fine person. Although we came from different portions of the spectrum, we took the time to understand the other's point of view. Out of that grew mutual respect, though we disagree with fundimental principles. It is the quality of the person and not so much what the person believes, that sets the tone of the interaction. I respect the courage of someones conviction when my convictions are treated with respect in kind.<br><br>
On the other hand, when someone out of the blue strolls by and calls me &quot;baby killer&quot; for no reason other than the fact that I am a Vietnam Veteran and I exist, anything can happen. Sure, I have PTSD, and I am learning to work with it, but that is secondary to my reaction to being insulted. You can be any person on the street and be insulted by that. I have pride and self esteem, and I will return that which was given, and then I will rip their heads off.<br><br>
If a Vietnam Veteran treated someone else like that, I would expect a similar reactive situation in kind. That has happened here, too, though less frequently. All is fair.<br><br>
There are gamesters on this site who post anonymously whose posts are designed to push buttons in all camps. Perhaps they enjoy watching the turmoil they cause, and derive a high from it. Firesetters have a similar problem.<br><br>
There is a concerted effort on this site to ignore provocative and foul languaged posts. In large, this is becomming more successful as time goes on. Not all people progress at the same rates, including myself, but the net effect is to make the site safer for others to post their thoughts and feelings. Recent activity on the upper threads bears this out.<br><br>
DocDel, if you came to me and said I respect your personal decisions but I disagree with your point of view, you know there would be no problem with me in continued constructive discussion. However, if you came to me and said I was a worthless piece of babykilling shit who deserves to die, and you disagreed with my point of view, my reaction would be spectacular. <br><br>
Of all the faults I have found on this site, the lack of respect for another's personal decisions is perhaps the most significant. That is the fault of the disrespectful person, however, and not of the site.<br><br>
I, too, miss many who choose to no longer post here, for whatever reason. However, we cannot go back to the past. We can encourage decent civil dialog and try to make it a safe place for anyone to post without fear of derision or discrimination.<br><br>
